\begin_layout Subsection
The same cross section with the same parameters except for a muck lower variance of the conductivity,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $var(\ln\left(k\right))$
\end_inset

 is 1.1 instead of 6.6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The more homogeneous the aquifer,
 the more the breakthrough will conform to Fickian or Gaussian character with more symmetrical breakthrough curves and histograms.
 We can test this with the same model by just changing the variance of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 field from 6.6 in the previous case to 
\begin_inset Formula $1.5$
\end_inset

,
 a value which I deem more realistic for the more homogeneous aquifers found in the Netherlands.
 The results are given in the figures below.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim11-kfield"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 looks similar to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim-kfield"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 however,
 the colorbar below it shows that the values are different,
 and less extreme.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim11-stream"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows that although the streamlines still go up and down along their paths,
 these fluctuations are now much less than those in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:stream-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Also,
 the head contours are much more straight in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim11-stream"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 than in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:stream-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is also due to the more homogeneous aquifer that we created in this section.
 As expected,
 the cumulative breakthrough curves now show much more symmetry about the 50% value,
 with far a less extreme tail.
 In fact,
 except for the small asymmetry in the last curve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1000$
\end_inset

 m,
 asymmetry are essentially absent for all shorter travel distances.
 Hence,
 all breakthrough curves are now essentially Gaussian.
 The symmetry of the breakthough behavior is also reveiled by the histograms and jumps into the eye when comparing figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim11-t-hist"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim-hist_t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
