\begin_layout Subsection
Regular Gaussian conductivity field with the same parameters as used in the MIM model of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Made-cross-section"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MIM model to simulate the MADE breakthrough curves in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fiori13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 uses blocks of width 
\begin_inset Formula $2R$
\end_inset

,
 essentially 
\begin_inset Formula $2I_{h}$
\end_inset

 with each having a constant conductivity throughout the block,
 while these block conductivities area conform the statistics for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $var\left(\ln\left(k\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 and for the integration lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead of using blocks,
 it may be feasible to simply generate a cross-section that fulfills these condictions but without resorting to the blocks of the MIM model.
 The cross section generated this way,
 is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gaus-kfield"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 It lacks the block structure,
 which characterizes the cross section of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim-kfield"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The stream and head lines in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gaus-stream"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 are as irregular as in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:stream-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which is due to the same large log-conductivity variance used in these two cases.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gaus-cum-t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the breakthrough curves.
 The top figure shown those belonging to the current conductivity field,
 while,
 for easy comparison,
 the bottom figure is the same as figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim-cum-t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for the model with the block structure,
 but otherwise the same parameters.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gaus-cum-t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 makes clear that,
 also with a fully continuous Gaussian field,
 similar breakthrough curves are obtained as with a MIM-type model with blocks.
 Probably it is just the applied range of the horizontal and vertical variograms that matter to get a behavior characteristic of preferential flow path,
 while it does matter little if a block structure is added.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gaus-hist-t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 on top,
 shows the histograms derived from the breakthrough curves for this continuous cross section,
 and at the bottom,
 again for easy comparison,
 those obtained with the block structure and otherwise the same parameters already shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mim-hist_t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 I would argue that both figures are not too different.
 They are essentially characterized by asymmetry with a large tail,
 which is what one expects from a strongly heterogeneous aquifer.
\end_layout

