\begin_layout Section
Wim's aquifer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In his papers,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand nocite
key "Lange20,Lange22,Lange25"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 simulates the dispersion using an artificial aquifer built of blocks,
 he calls domains of given size that are place next to each other and on top of each other as to fill the entire cross section of the aquifer.
 Each block as a low background conductivity and includes an elongated facies with a high conductivity.
 The background and high facies conductivities are the same in each block.
 For this example they are chose to be 5 and 500 m/d respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like in the previous examples the cross section has the same size,
 100 m deep and 1000 m wide with cells of 1x1 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Each block was given the size of 20 cells along the x-axis and 5 cells along the z-axis.
 The facies was placed randomly inside each block.
 The inner facies was given the size of 20 cells along the x-axis and 1 cell along the z-axis.
 This is about what De Lange uses in his example pictures.
 The boundary conditions are the same as in the previous examples,
 a gradient of 0.0036 and a porosity of 0.31.
 The results of the simulation are in the following pictures.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:wdl-kfield"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 field,
 i.e.
 one background conductivity and one facies conductivity according to the header of the figure.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:wdl-stream"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the streamline and the head contours.
 The high-conductive inclusions clearly distort and channel the flow through them.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:wdl-cum-t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows the cumulative breakthrough curves for different locations along the cross section.
 They are not symmetric due to the hetergeneous character of the aquifer.
 However,
 the asymmetry can be deemed not so high as expectec.
 The same conclusion can be drawn from the histograms in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:wdl-hist-t"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 they are far less asymmetric than expected.
 Therefore,
 they might be reasonably modelled by a more tranditional Fickian model.
 Perhaps the number of inclusions or their lengths are to small to deem this aquifer a really heterogeneous despite the large contract between the background and the facies conductivities.
\end_layout

