\begin_layout Subsection
Test case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's important to run a test case that allows verification of the procedures.
 The chosen test case has the same cross section of 100 rows and 1000 columns with cells of 1x1 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The aquifer is,
 therefore,
 100 m thick and 1000 m long.
 The porosity and the is kept the same as before.
 The fixed gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $J=0.0036$
\end_inset

 was multiplied by 50 to make sure the fastest particles reach the end of the model within given by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $hL=180$
\end_inset

 m instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $3.6$
\end_inset

 m and letting 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{R}=0$
\end_inset

 m.
 The section was divided into 10 blocks of 10 model layers each.
 The conductivity is constant in each block and increases in 10 steps from 1 m/d to 10 m/d.
 Hence the first 10 model layers all have 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 m/d,
 the model layers 11 through 20 have 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

 m/d and so on until layers 91 through 100,
 which all have 
\begin_inset Formula $k=100$
\end_inset

 m/d.
 With this setup,
 the discharge through each layer and the travel time in them as well as the location of each particle at any time are now know and can be verified in the outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean conductivity equals 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{mean}=5.5$
\end_inset

 m/d and the total discharge 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=k_{mean}\times D\times J=0.55\times100\times0.0036=1.98$
\end_inset

 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/d.
 The Modflow list file gives 1.98 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/s.
 The hand and Modpath compute travel times are also essentially the same as the ones computed by Modflow,
 for all xObs distances and all layers.
 Finally the postions of the particles at the chosen observation times.
\end_layout

