\begin_layout Section
Summarizing the discussion on dispersion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A phenomenon,
 including that of dispersion of a pollutant in moving groundwater,
 can often be best understood by looking at its behavior or results in extreme situations.
 We may,
 therefore,
 ask ourselves how dispersion develops in the following two extreme cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Uniform flow in a perfectly homogenious aquifer,
 with grains as fine as the water molucules themselves.
 Hence,
 there are no velocity variations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Flow in an aquifer that is layered and heterogeneous to the extreme.
 Hence,
 it consists of two parallel layers one with (almost) zero conductivity and the other with some distinct conductivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over these cases,
 we may drape the process of diffusion,
 which is known to always work and does so at its own pace,
 irrespective of the actual velocity of the groundwater itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first case,
 the only movement of particles is the progress of the front,
 initally flat and pependicular to the flow,
 which will always remain sharp and stay perfectly flat.
 The only thing diffusion does is to cause some spread in longitudinal direction.
 Without diffusion,
 the breakthrough curve would be vertical.
 With diffusion it would still be very steep.
 The breakthrough curve would be fully described by the average front position and its standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{2D_{d}t}$
\end_inset

.
 Even if the particles would be subject to some small-scale random velocity varations,
 the front will have the same properties,
 with a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 that will be larger than that caused by molecular diffusion,
 probably even be much larger,
 but would still follow this expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{2Dt}$
\end_inset

.
 Only now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{v}+D_{d}$
\end_inset

 and since the random velocity differences are proportional to the groundwater velocity itself,
 we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $D=a_{L}v+D_{d}$
\end_inset

 and the process would be fully Gaussian and Fickian,
 with a head and tail of the same length and shape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second extreme case,
 a part,
 may be half of the water will be funelled through the high-conductive layer,
 with the rest lagging far behind.
 When we call the situation at some point in time also a plume,
 we see that we have a head and a tail completely defined by the velocities in the two layers.
 Let the velocity in the two layers be 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 with conductivities 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively and a gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and porosity 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v_{1} & =k_{1}i/\theta\\
v_{2} & =k_{2}i\theta
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total discharge through the aquifer then equals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q\theta=D_{1}k_{1}i+D_{2}k_{2}i=Dk_{m}i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 the thicknesse of the respective zones and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 the aquifer thickness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that the same amoun of water flows through both zones,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}k_{1}=D_{2}k_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k_{m} & =2\frac{D_{1}}{D}k_{1}\\
k_{m} & =2\frac{D_{2}}{D}k_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are still free to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}/k_{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}/D_{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}/D$
\end_inset

 for that matter.
 Just take 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}=0.1D_{2}$
\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}=10k_{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k_{m} & =2\frac{0.1}{1.1}k_{1}\approx0.19k_{1}\rightarrow k_{1}\approx5.3k_{m}\\
k_{m} & =2\frac{0.9}{1.1}k_{2}\approx1.64k_{2}\rightarrow k_{2}\approx0.61k_{m}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could even take a more extreme case in which 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}=0.001D_{2}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}=1000k_{2}$
\end_inset

 yielding 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{m}=2\frac{0.001}{1.001}k_{1}=2\frac{0.999}{1.001}k_{2}\approx0.002k_{1}\approx2k_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in which still half of the discharge flows through the thin conductive layer and the other half through the thick layer with the lower conductivity.
 In these,
 cases,
 even when equal amounts of water pass through both zones,
 the distance traveled in the fast,
 high-conductive zone is more than 5 to 500 times the average traveled distance,
 and that in the low-conductive zone is about 60% to 50% of the average traveled distance,
 where 50% is the limit case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens if we sample the water by means of a well that extracts all the water at a certain point?
 Then,
 as soon as the fast front passed this point,
 the relative concentration would jump to 0.5 to remain constant until the tail passes,
 at which point the relative concentration would jump further to 1.0.
 From these samples one could conclude that the mean of the front would lie half way between the two mentioned times and that its spread would amount to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\frac{t_{1}-t_{2}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
 if one samples the aquifer without actually extracting water by a well,
 for instance by means of a device that can measure some quality aspect in situ at any depth,
 and if we then take the mean along the vertical,
 a completely different breakthrough curve would emerge.
 As the fast zone has only one tenth or even one thousandth of the thickness of that of the slow zone,
 the relative concentration would,
 after passing the sampling location,
 only jump up to 0.1 or to 0.001 instead of 0.5 and would rise to 1.
 0 after passage of the front in the slow zone.
 Therefore,
 the way of sampling may make a huge difference in the outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What also jumps into mind in this extreme case,
 is that the spread,
 i.e.
 the distance between head and tail,
 grows proportionally to time and,
 therfore with distance.
 In the case of Fickian disperion it grows proportional to the root of time.
 Reality will likely pop up somewhere in between.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we drape diffusion or our ignored random small-scale velocity velocity variations over the last situation,
 there will be some longitudinal dispersion,
 which may be negligible relative to the fast moving head of the front.
 However,
 we will also see some dispersion across the horziontal line separting the two zones.
 The importance of this sideways spreading depends on the magnitude of the process,
 or perhaps to the absolute speed of the groundwater relative to diffusion.
 Nevertheless,
 if one imagines a very large sideways dispersion,
 it would cause the head of the front to loose concentration to the water in the slow zone.
 The larger this process the more the end result will resemble Fickian behavior.
 Imagine that the fast zone were split into a vast number of subzones spread out over the vertical but still making sure that the combined transmissivity of these fast subzones remains equal to that of the original one.
 This would make diffusion dominant instead of negligible,
 even with the same overal transmissivities,
 conductivities and zone thicknesses;
 it would completely alter the shape of the front.
 Hence,
 size or layering matters.
 This includes time as it affects the size of the spread by diffusion,
 which,
 as we have seen will grow to aquifer-height proportions if sufficiently long.
 Even much shorter times may be important if the fast and the slow layers are thin.
 Reality will always be somewhere in between.
 The more homogeneous the aquifer,
 or the thinner the layers,
 the more Fickian the dispersion process will be.
 The more heterogeneous in the sense that the flow is more dominated by preferential flow paths,
 the less Fickian the dispersion will be,
 and the more its spread with grow linearly with time and distance.
 Because the streamlines in real-world cases will pass through sequences of zones of higher and lower conductivties of different extent,
 the spread may grow towards linear with traveled distance,
 the larger the probability of encountering high-conductivity zones of even larger exent that channel the grounwater along preferential paths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary and conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dispersion during subsurfacde mass transpport was studied based on recent papers as mentioned in the references.
 The phenomemon of dispersion is still not totally tackeled in models as well as in theory.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zheng11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 mentioned the dual medium feature,
 adding kinematic sorption,
 that was built into the MT3DMS mass transport model to better capture the observations of tracer tests in the Made test side 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zheng11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However,
 the improved match may well have been reached for the wrong reasons,
 as there was no sorption active at the site during the bromium tracer test.
 At least 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fiori13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 showed that a similarly accurate result could be reached with their MIM (multi indicator model),
 which only took advection into account.
 The problem is believed to has been the impossibility to characterize and model the heterogeneous conductivity field in the subsurface accurately enough,
 because therein seems to lie the key to successfully model subsurface displacement of pollutants and successfully include match the observed dispersion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is generally known that in real-world situations flow along preferential paths is often dominant.
 At the same time,
 it is extremely hard to predict beforehand based on methods available to characterize the subsruface's conductivity field in all three dimensions.
 While in more homogeneous aquifers dispersion tends toward Fickian behavior,
 in heterogeneous aquifers it does not.
 Fickian behavior sees dispersion as a Gaussian process,
 which yields symmetrical breakthrough curves and histograms with the spread that grows according to the square root of the traveled distance.
 However,
 non Fickian behavior as observed in hetrogeneous aquifers,
 show asymmetrical breakhrough curves and histograms,
 with early breakthorugh and a large tail,
 with an associated spread that grows linearly with travel distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This non-Fickian behavior was shown by modelling a heterogeneous aquifer with the properties of the Made site (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fiori13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The aquifer generated with those parameter values,
 was similar to that by which 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fiori13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 were able to reasonably well model the bromide tracer test at the Made site.
 The results show indeed that the breaktrough curves and breakthrough histograms have an early breakthrough with a long tail.
 The opposite,
 more Fickian result was obtained by modeling another cross section generated with the same parameters,
 but with a far lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 variance,
 which resulted in a much more homogeneous aquifer.
 The aquifer used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fiori13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 consisted of blocks with a length of around 20 m based on the horizontal integration scale (range of the semi-variogram).
 Each block got a conductivity value chosen from a generated random field with the proper statistical values.
 In the third example,
 we left the block structure out and directly used the statistically generated conductivity field.
 The results show that they are similar to those of the first example,
 generated with the same statistical parameter values (see the header of each figure for the values used).
 Hence,
 using the block structure does not seem to add much to the results;
 only the horizontal and verticla semi-variograms used to generate the random field seem to matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 a cross section was generated alike the one De Lange uses in his papers to demonstrate and simulate dispersion in very heterogeneous aquifers.
 De Lange,
 for the sake of modelling dispersion,
 sees the aquifer as layers of equally sized blocks called domains,
 which are put next to and on top of each other to fill the aquifer.
 Each block has a low background conductivity (of 5 m/d) and holds an elongated,
 rectangular inclusion with a high conductivity (of 500 m/d).
 This cross section was simulated in the same way as the previous ones.
 Expected was a strong non-Fickian behavior to show up in the breakthrough curves and the histograms.
 However,
 this proved hardly the case.
 So perhaps the cross section was not heterogeneous enough,
 despite the 100-fold conductiviy contrast between the background and the included facies conductivities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Referenties}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analysis of the lognormal distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathtt{if}\,T\sim LogNormal\left(\mu,\sigma\right)\rightarrow\log T\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When retrieving the lognormal distribution or generating it,
 it has three parameters scale,
 loc,
 shape,
 where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\ln\left(scale\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=shape$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $loc$
\end_inset

=linear shift in the time domain (real world domain)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\sim LogNormal\left(\mu,\sigma,\mathtt{loc}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is equivalent to saying
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln\left(t-\mathtt{loc}\right)\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or,
 rearranged
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\mathtt{loc}+\exp\left(X\right),\,\,\,\,X\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Hence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{loc}$
\end_inset

 acts as a shift in the time domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It's the minimum value the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 can take – the distribution is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $t>\mathtt{loc}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It's ofteh use to delya th eonset of the lognormal process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further properties of the lognormal distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathtt{mean}\left(t\right)=\mathtt{loc}+\exp\left(\mu+\frac{\sigma^{2}}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathtt{median}\left(t\right)=\mathtt{loc}+\exp\left(\mu\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathtt{mode}\left(t\right)=\mathtt{loc}+\exp\left(\mu-\sigma^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Head and tail quantiles may be useful,
 but more so in log-space than in real-space due to the skewness of the lognormal distribution.
 The quantile times s 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{05}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{16}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{50}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{84}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{95}$
\end_inset

 can also easily obtained from a given cdf or pdf distribution,
 but these too are less informative for the lognormal distribution than for the normal distribution.
 
\end_layout

